Adds complete repository management to the Runtipi CLI for managing app stores and to avoid command running while outside main runtipi dirctory.

## ðŸ†• What's New

### Commands Added
```bash
runtipi repo list                    # Show all repositories
runtipi repo add <name> <url>        # Add new repository  
runtipi repo remove <name>           # Remove repository
runtipi repo update                  # Update all repositories
```

### Example Usage
```bash
# Add the community app store
runtipi repo add community-apps https://github.com/runtipi/runtipi-appstore

# List all configured repositories
runtipi repo list

# Update repositories to get latest apps
runtipi repo update
```

## ðŸ”’ Security Improvement

**Directory Validation**: The CLI now enforces execution only within a valid Runtipi installation directory. Commands will fail with a clear error message if run outside the proper Runtipi folder, preventing accidental execution in wrong locations.

## âš ï¸ Important Notice

> **Repository Remove Behavior**: The API currently returns `200 OK` even when trying to remove non-existent repositories. The CLI will show "success" but users should check Runtipi logs for actual removal status. This behavior is documented in the code with a comment for future reference if the API behavior changes.

- **New file**: `internal/commands/repo.go` - Repository command implementation
- **Updated**: `internal/types/args.go` - Added `RepoArgs` and `RepoCommand` types  
- **Updated**: `cmd/runtipi/main.go` - Integrated repo commands + directory validation
- **Enhanced**: Directory validation logic using `.env` file detection

## âœ¨ Features

- âœ… **Smart error handling** - Clear messages for duplicate names, invalid URLs
- âœ… **Beautiful output** - Formatted repository listing with emojis and status  
- âœ… **Cross-platform** - Works on Windows, Linux, and ARM64 (Raspberry Pi)
- âœ… **Consistent UX** - Follows same patterns as existing app commands
- âœ… **Directory safety** - Prevents execution outside Runtipi installations
- âœ… **API quirks documented** - Known limitations clearly marked for future maintenance

I am not a fan of the implementation here. You are making your life harder than it needs to be. Ideally you would to create a struct containing the API response. For example for the `/all` endpoint you would do:

```go
type Appstore struct {
  Slug string `json:"slug"`
  Name string `json:"name"`
  Url string `json:"url"`
  Enabled bool `json:"enabled"`
}

type AppstoresResponse struct {
  Appstores Appstore `json:"appstores"`
}
```

Then in the API response you can unmarshall the body to the struct and easily access your data. Since we are not dealing with methods you can use [type parameters](https://go.dev/tour/generics/1) which will make your API function look something like this:

```go
func handleRepoAPIResponse[R any](spin *components.Spinner, resp *http.Response, err error, successMessage, errorMessage string, response R) (R, error) { ... }
```

Now this function should take an input struct, check if the request succeeded then try to decode the body to the given struct and return it.

In addition when you are posting data (creating, modifying etc) you can either do it the quick and dirty way like we do it [here](https://github.com/runtipi/cli/blob/1197296c54002ff67c9fe7dec52414bef82a556b/internal/commands/app.go#L113) or use a proper struct to hold the values and then marshall it. Same thing with the error, instead of using a map use a proper struct to handle the response.

*Note: Because go doesn't support enums you can't do either the struct I expected or the response but what you can do is add the `status` and `message` keys in the `AppstoreResponse` struct from above and then check if they are empty (indicating no error) in the decode.*

Lastly I also do like the code rabbit suggestion that says to escape the repository name.

issue.title: Rowan pip missing dependency
issue.body:
Hello,

When I compare the import modules in python file  with dependencies in the `package.xml` for the package `crazyfile_py`, I found the `rowan` module is missing.

The module is added in the `crazyfile_py/crazyfile_py/crazyfile.py`:
```
import rclpy
import rclpy.node
import rowan
```

But it is not declared in the `package.xml`. So `rosdep` might not work correctly and could not install all the needed dependencies.

So could you tell me if it is necessary to add the dependency in the `package.xml`?
Thanks!

comment.body:
Hi!

It wasn't added to package.xml as it didn't exist in ros-dep distro, but it has been recently merged: https://github.com/ros/rosdistro/pull/46855. I just didn't had the time yet to add this to package.xml

So you can add it as 'python3-rowan-pip' if you want, feel free to make a PR!

A sidenote, I've learned that these pip packages will not be included in the build of the released packages, so the installation instructions will need to include a rosdep install. Inthe future we will need to consider writing these equations full out in the script itself to reduce the dependencies. That should be too hard to do.

issue.title: FIX: Virtual Network Resource Group dependency
issue.body: # Overview/summary This pull request fixes the issue where terraform was throwing a 404 error ResourceGroupNotFound when trying to deploy a route table or network security group into the virtual network resource group. By moving the resource_group_data logic out of the virtual network module and moving it to be used against the resource group module allows the network resource group to be created before any network resources if set to enabled. ## This PR fixes/adds/changes/removes 1. fixes #473 ### Breaking changes 1. Existing deployments may try to replace the resources if they are ran again due to the Network resource group being created in a new module. ## Testing evidence Please provide testing evidence to show that your Pull Request works/fixes as described and documented above. This has been tested locally based on several scenarios: - resource_group_creation_enabled and resource_group_creation_enabled within the virtual network variable both set to false - resource_group_creation_enabled set to false and resource_group_creation_enabled within the virtual network variable set to true - resource_group_creation_enabled set to true and resource_group_creation_enabled within the virtual network variable set to false Below is a screenshot of the resources deployed into the same resource group ## As part of this pull request I have - [x] Checked for duplicate [Pull Requests](https://github.com/Azure/terraform-azurerm-lz-vending/pulls) - [x] Associated it with relevant [issues](https://github.com/Azure/terraform-azurerm-lz-vending/issues), for tracking and closure. - [x] Run and `make fmt` & `make docs` to format your code and update documentation. - [x] Created unit and deployment tests and provided evidence. - [x] Updated relevant and associated documentation.
